<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> Introducing Missions   <br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.40)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=2090'>Scott "CategoryOneGame" Church</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=2090&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 4, 2010</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Virtual Block 7 will introduce a few exciting concepts and mechanics to SWCCG. While this is spoiler week, and there will be some spoilers coming later on, before we got to actual cards I wanted to explain one of the most unprecedented moves being taken in this set.<br />
<br />
For the first time in almost 10 years, this June will see a new card type introduced to StarWarsCCG. The new card type, Missions, was designed partially to fill the gap between Epic Events and objectives. Epic Events started as just that - truly momentous occasions from the Star Wars Trilogy transcendent into SWCCG. However, starting with Deciphers final few, they became more of a mechanical convenience and a way to flavor an objective or theme, or a way around text limits for an objective. This is unauthentic to the intent of StarWars and thus problematic.<br />
<br />
Additionally there was another way that had been used to provide thematic design - the use of effects. Effects have been used extensively, perhaps excessively in the past, and did in some sense have a natural place as a thematic device. However there are a few problems with effects for this type of use. Firstly, effects don&#39;t require commitment. It is possible to use No Bargain v to completely change the rules of the game mid-game, essentially getting around the restrictions that it forces on the player. This type of flexibility can be good for the game, but it is not necessarily good for every theme, indeed for a few it is somewhat anti-thematic. In any case its difficult to test all the effect interactions because there is somewhat of a critical mass of effects in the game. Additionally, almost every effect that is easily virtualized has been so at this point, which causes further limitations.<br />
<br />
Thus, Design created missions. While it was desired to allow for more flavor with how games are played, missions are not designed with incredible new mechanics in mind, but rather as a way of consolidating the type of thematic consistency already available from cards like Imperial Domination (v), Scum and Villainy, Epic Duel (v), and especially Insurrection (v) and No Bargain (v). There are currently plans for 2 types of missions, regular and critical. The only inherent difference is that only 1 critical mission may be played on table per player per game. Missions are more theme-based than other cards, so they sometimes aren&#39;t exactly a bonus, but just a different flavor, like Black Sun and Mistryl (the ISB mission, for instance, isn&#39;t a specific ISB helper, just an ISB theme). Being so close to worlds, we made these as a sampling of the Mission concept, which is why there&#39;s a bit of variations in power and application. We currently anticipate a total of 6 missions being released in the first set of Darkness Rising.<br />
<br />
•In The Hands Of The ISB [•Fondor (V)] 2<br />
[Virtual Set 7.1 - Special Edition - U]<br />
CRITICAL MISSION<br />
Text: Deploy on ISB Central Office. This site is a prison (if opponent controls, all captives here are released). Total ability of 6 or more required for opponent to draw battle destiny here. Whenever an ISB agent delivers a captive here, opponent loses 4 Force (once per captive per captivity). ISB agents may escort captives and, if escorting a captive during your move phase, may use 1 Force to relocate escort and captive to a related docking bay (as a regular move). Once during your move phase, may use 2 Force to relocate (as a regular move) an ISB agent present with Ice-Heart here to a site you control.<br />
[Objective] [Setup]<br />
Set Icon 7.1•X<br />
<br />
•Prepared Defenses (V) 3<br />
[Virtual Set 7.1 - Death Star II - C]<br />
USED OR STARTING INTERRUPT<br />
Text: USED: / one Death Squadron Star Destroyer, a Dreadnaught, or a Victory-class Star Destroyer. STARTING: / up to three [Setup] cards or Effects that deploy on table for free and are always [Immune to Alter]. Place Interrupt in Lost Pile.<br />
Set Icon 7.1•X<br />
<br />
There are a few other things to know about missions. Some of them will be compatible with objectives, others will not. Missions which can be played with an objective will have an objective icon on the card to identify it as such. Also, missions will come into play in a couple of ways. They can come during regular play, or, more typically, can be started with cards which allow them to be started. The [setup] icon was introduced in the last set on the card the camp v. Many missions will have this icon so that cards which allow starting of [setup] icons will allow the starting of missions on table. There will be new starting interrupts this set to incorporate the use of [setup] icons as a starting option.<br />
<br />
All information provided here has been produced by Mark and the Marketing Team for V7. <br />
<br />
This is not my article.  I&#39;ll be posting an article about ISB and a look at the way that the deck can be played.   <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/starwarsccg/articles/articles.php?id=6596&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/starwarsccg/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/starwarsccg/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table>
